<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="266" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1477,2007]" pageId="15" pageNumber="266">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1693,1719]" pageId="15" pageNumber="266">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small species (TL: 3.5–4.0 mm), oblong-oval species, lateral sides of elytra nearly parallel in basal two thirds of their length. Head reddish; pronotum dark brown with reddish anterior margin and lateral sides; elytra brownish black, with broadly orange base and thin lateral orange band broadening posteriorly to lateral subapical spot. Pronotum with several short strioles basally and laterally. Each elytron with five longitudinal discal striae: all striae beginning at base and ending approximately in apical fifth of elytral length (
<figureCitation box="[1096,1181,1837,1864]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–16" captionStartId="34.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[214,1373,200,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-23@34.[196,1391,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURES 13–16. Habitus of Copelatus in China. 13. C. nanlingensis sp. nov. (holotype ♂; Dadongshan, Guangdong); 14. C. oblitus (♂; Cotai Ecological Zone, Macao); 15. C. oblitus (♀; Lantau, Hongkong); 16. C. parallelus (♀; Shanghai). Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6410719" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6410719/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="266">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). Median lobe simple, sickle shaped, broad (widest at middle), only slightly narrowing to beak-shaped apex (Fig. 51). Parameres broad, ‘D’-shaped; apex long and slender; apical lobes long, club-shaped (Fig. 52). Female similar to male in habitus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="266" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1477,2007]" pageId="15" pageNumber="266">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1945,1971]" pageId="15" pageNumber="266">Distribution.</emphasis>
A species described from Japan and recently recorded also from Korea (
<bibRefCitation author="Jung, S. W. &amp; Min, H. K. &amp; Lee, D. - H." box="[1172,1360,1945,1971]" pageId="15" pageNumber="266" pagination="128 - 138" refId="ref32686" refString="Jung, S. W., Min, H. K. &amp; Lee, D. - H. (2020) Aquatic beetles fauna in Nohwa and Bogil Islands, and Copelatus parallelus (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae) and Scirtes sobrinus (Coleoptera: Scirtidae) new to South Korea. Animal Systematics, Evolution, and Diversity, 36 (2), 128 - 138. https: // doi. org / 10.5635 / ASED. 2020.36.2.004" type="journal article" year="2020">
Jung 
<emphasis box="[1234,1291,1945,1971]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="266">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="266">
First records from 
<collectingCountry box="[313,386,1981,2007]" name="China" pageId="15" pageNumber="266">China</collectingCountry>
(
